snippet.title: Dang Wangi police chief injured in standoff with Kg Sg Baru residents
snippet.description:
Dang Wangi police chief Assistant Commissioner Sulizmie Affendy Sulaiman was left injured in a scuffle with 
Kampung Sungai Baru residents following a court-ordered operation to demolish houses there today. 

Sulizmie Affendy was seen with a bloodied face following an encounter with residents who were attempting to enter the area.

Police have asked residents to disperse.

snippet.title: Ipoh blast: Cops tracking down 2 suspects
snippet.description:
Police are actively tracking down two men suspected of bombing a business premises at Panorama Lapangan Perdana here early yesterday morning.

The explosion damaged two shop units, but no fatalities or injuries were reported.

Ipoh district police chief, Assistant Commissioner Abang Zainal Abidin Abang Ahmad, said police received information on the incident, which occurred at 4.58am yesterday (Aug 31), from a 43-year-old woman.

He said closed-circuit television (CCTV) footage from the premises showed two men on a motorcycle placing an object in front of the shop before leaving.

Initial checks by the Post Blast Investigation Unit and the Weapons Unit of the Perak police contingent headquarters confirmed that the incident was caused by a low-grade explosive device.

snippet.title: Drone footage reveals widespread flooding in Penampang after relentless rain
snippet.description:
Widespread flooding and landslides have been reported across Penampang after the Moyog River burst its banks for the fourth time in a week, following days of relentless heavy rain.

Former senator Adrian Banie Lasimbang, in a Facebook post accompanied by aerial footage captured by drone pilot Philip Chin, highlighted extensive inundation at several locations, including Sigah Roundabout, SM St Michael, Kampung Dabak, Penampang Proper, Dungkahang, Tanaki, Nampasan, Kasigui, Kibabaig, Tuavon, and Kivatu.

The images were taken at 1.30pm today. 

He added that several relief centres have been set up to provide temporary shelters during these challenging times.

snippet.title: 'He just left the house'   Father in shock over son's fatal stabbing
snippet.description:
The father of a 30-year-old man who was fatally stabbed said his son had only left their home briefly before the incident.

The man, in his 60s, recalled his son telling him that he would be going out for a while, and not long after, police arrived to inform him of what had happened.

He said he had heard of such cases but never imagined it would happen to his own family.

The victim and a 28-year-old woman were found dead last night in Taman Nona with stab wounds. Police are investigating, but no arrests have been made.

The grieving father described his son as a good and dependable child, saying he had expected to die first, but now his son had gone before him.

snippet.title: Roundup: Israel intercepts Gaza flotilla, 12 Malaysians abducted
snippet.description:
The Sumud Nusantara Flotilla Command Centre (SNCC) confirmed that contact was lost with 12 Malaysians on five vessels after Israeli forces intercepted their ships late last night (Gaza time).

The Global Sumud Flotilla (GSF) was less than 80 nautical miles (148km) from Gaza when more than 20 Israeli naval vessels closed in, ordering the convoy to change course. Activists said the manoeuvre was aimed at enforcing a blockade.

SNCC director-general Datuk Dr Sani Araby Abdul Alim said a red alert was issued at 1.34am today, just before the ‘Alma’ entered Level 2 of the Red Zone near the Gaza coastline.

Malaysian humanitarian volunteer and actress Ardell Aryana, on board one of the vessels, said there were moments of sheer terror as they came under Israeli attack. In a live SOS broadcast, she said her team was left drenched and freezing amid strong winds and rough seas.

Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim vowed Malaysia would “go all out” to hold Israel accountable, particularly over the safety of Malaysian citizens.

Meanwhile, the Malaysian United Democratic Alliance (Muda) demanded the immediate and unconditional release of the 12 Malaysians allegedly abducted from the flotilla.

Despite repeated Israeli attempts to block them, 30 other flotilla vessels remained on course towards Gaza early this morning.

snippet.title: Raja Muda Selangor tours Media Prima headquarters
snippet.description:
Raja Muda of Selangor, Tengku Amir Shah Sultan Sharafuddin Idris Shah, today visited Balai Berita, the headquarters of Media Prima Bhd (MPB).

Tengku Amir Shah was welcomed by MPB group chairman Datuk Seri Dr Syed Hussian Aljunid, MPB group managing director Datuk Rafiq Razali, Media Prima Omnia chief operating officer Datuk Mohd Efendi Omar, and News and Current Affairs group managing editor Jasbant Singh.

Also present were Berita Harian group editor Zulkifli Jalil, Harian Metro group editor Husain Jahit, and New Straits Times' associate editor Najmuddin Najib.

During the three-hour visit, Tengku Amir Shah was briefed on MPB’s television, print, digital, and radio operations. He also recorded a news reading for the NST’s Heard The News initiative, which will appear in tomorrow’s editions.

To commemorate the occasion, he received a framed copy of the New Straits Times front page dated Dec 12, 1990 — his birthday.

snippet.title: Tang Jie–Ee Wei go from volatile to cool
snippet.description:
Malaysia’s mixed doubles pair Chen Tang Jie and Toh Ee Wei are no longer volatile or pointing fingers — and that transformation has delighted head coach Nova Widianto.

After winning their historic world title last month, Nova says the duo have become calmer, stronger, and able to handle setbacks without turning on each other.

Ranked world No.4, Tang Jie–Ee Wei have already beaten the world’s top three pairs from China and Thailand. Nova believes they must now focus on consistency, with mixed doubles wide open following the retirement of Olympic champions Zheng Si Wei–Huang Ya Qiong.

Ee Wei is now recovering from a minor muscle strain but will return in time for the European circuit.

snippet.title: Azam Baki: Malaysia has recovered RM30bil in 1MDB assets
snippet.description:
MACC chief commissioner Tan Sri Azam Baki said recovery efforts in the 1Malaysia Development Berhad (1MDB) scandal have so far yielded about RM30 billion, against initial losses estimated at RM42 billion.

Azam said 1MDB is internationally recognised as one of the world's biggest financial scandals, and recovery efforts remain underway with cooperation from countries including the United Kingdom, Switzerland, Barbados and Kuwait.

Between January and July this year, he said the MACC opened 728 investigation papers, of which 109 involved high-profile, public-interest and sensitive cases. The remaining 619 were classified as ordinary cases.

snippet.title: Nine remanded over murder probe linked to body found in car, cop shooting
snippet.description:
Nine people, including a woman, have been remanded for seven days to assist in investigations into the case of a woman's body found in a car with a suspect who stabbed and shot a policeman.

The remand order, effective today until next Sunday, was issued by magistrate Anis Hanini Abdullah when the suspects were brought to the magistrate's court here this morning.

The application for remand was made to facilitate investigations under Section 302 of the Penal Code for murder and Section 307 for attempted murder.

The female suspect is being remanded under Section 302, while the other eight male suspects are being remanded under Section 307 of the same code.

The nine, aged between their 20s and 60s, were seen entering the chamber at 10.30am before being escorted out in handcuffs by policemen about half an hour later.

snippet.title: Anwar: Stability in Indonesia and Thailand key to Asean unity
snippet.description:
Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said political stability in Indonesia and Thailand is vital for Asean's unity and Malaysia's bilateral ties with its neighbours.

The prime minister, who is the current Asean chairman, said Indonesian President Prabowo Subianto had told him during a meeting in Beijing that the situation in Jakarta was improving.

Indonesia recently faced widespread protests due to public dissatisfaction over lawmakers' allowances and rising living costs.

Tensions escalated after a motorcycle taxi driver was killed during a demonstration, leading to clashes with security forces.

On Thailand, Anwar expressed hope that the process of forming a new government would be expedited, adding that Malaysia was ready to engage with Bangkok once political stability was restored.

snippet.title: Teargas as Italy rallies for Palestine
snippet.description:
Tens of thousands protested across Italy on Monday, denouncing what they called genocide in Gaza. The nationwide day of action included strikes, marches, and blockades, with major clashes erupting in Milan where protesters burned a US flag and confronted police at the central station. Teargas was fired as projectiles were thrown and windows smashed.

In Rome, around 20,000 gathered at Termini station chanting "Free Palestine", while over 10,000 marched in Bologna, briefly blocking a motorway before police used water cannons. Demonstrations also took place in Turin, Florence, Naples, and Sicily, with dock workers blockading ports in Genoa and Livorno.

The protests coincided with moves by France and others at the UN to recognise a Palestinian state—already backed by the UK, Australia, and Canada. Italy's government, led by Prime Minister Giorgia Meloni, has said it will not follow suit. A 24-hour national strike was organised by the USB union to demand the severing of ties with Israel.

snippet.title: National shuttlers return to heroes' welcome after World Championships
snippet.description:
Badminton world champions Chen Tang Jie and Toh Ee Wei, along with women’s doubles runners-up Pearly Tan and M. Thinaah, received a heroes’ welcome at Kuala Lumpur International Airport.

The quartet touched down at 5.51am and were greeted by fans, family, and friends.

The KLIA arrival hall echoed with chants of “Malaysia Boleh” as banners waved high in celebration.

 Tang Jie and Ee Wei made history, clinching Malaysia’s first-ever world title in mixed doubles.

Pearly and Thinaah secured Malaysia’s first medal in women’s doubles — another milestone moment.

Welcoming them were Youth and Sports Minister Hannah Yeoh, the ministry's secretary-general Datuk Dr K. Nagulendran, and National Sports Council director-general Jefri Ngadirin, alongside BAM officials Datuk V. Subramaniam and Datuk Kenny Goh.

snippet.title: PH's limited seats in Sabah polls still significant, says Anwar
snippet.description:
Pakatan Harapan may contest a limited number of seats in the upcoming Sabah state election, but its chairman Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim says those few seats could prove decisive.

Speaking at the Himpunan Temu Rapat Umum 27 Years of Reformasi event in Kampung Kobuni, Anwar said PH would contest in select constituencies like Inanam, while collaborating with other parties elsewhere.

He emphasised the importance of a strong unity government to ensure smooth coordination between state and federal levels.

Although the exact number of seats was not revealed, Anwar confirmed continued cooperation with Barisan Nasional and Gabungan Rakyat Sabah—despite tensions between BN and GRS leaders.

He also thanked the public for their decades-long support, reflecting on his personal journey through hardship and political struggle.

snippet.title: 3 men get 7 years imprisonment for possessing dead female tiger
snippet.description:
Three men, including two brothers, were each sentenced to seven years in prison and fined RM250,000 by the Kota Tinggi Sessions Court for possessing a dead female Malayan tiger without a permit.

The accused, Md Shaheezam Md Salim, Nazerin Tomiran, and Mohamad Nazrol Tomiran, pleaded guilty to the offence, committed on Sept 16 at a petrol station in Felda Tenggaroh, Mersing.

They were found with the tiger in the rear of an MPV. The Malayan tiger is a fully protected species under the Wildlife Conservation Act 2010.

The trio was charged under Section 70(1) of the Act, which provides for up to 15 years' imprisonment upon conviction and a RM250,000 fine per protected animal.

snippet.title: Poachers nabbed with dead tiger in car
snippet.description:
A poacher’s attempt to keep a dead Malayan tiger was foiled in a raid at Felda Tenggaroh, Mersing, this morning. The operation was carried out by the Federal Reserve Unit (FRU) Intelligence Team with Johor Wildlife and National Parks Department (Perhilitan).

FRU commander Senior Assistant Commissioner Rosli Md Yusof said a tip-off led to the inspection of a Perodua Alza, where the remains of the Malayan tiger (Panthera Tigris Jacksoni) were discovered, believed to have been illegally poached.

Initial investigations revealed the three suspects had set snares for wild animals, but a tiger was caught instead. Owing to the animal’s high value, they allegedly tried to keep it but were tracked down by FRU intelligence.

The suspects, aged 28 to 49, were arrested for failing to produce a permit to keep wildlife. They, along with seized items, were taken to Mersing police headquarters for further action under the Wildlife Conservation Act 2010.

snippet.title: Indonesia seeks Oscar glory with time travel movie
snippet.description:
Imagine, if someone from your future pays you a visit, and reminds you of some ugly truths to be faced.
Such is the story of Sore: Istri Dari Masa Depan which is Indonesia's first time travel movie and the republic's 27th Oscar bid.

Sore stars Dion Wiyoko and Sheila Dara Aisha, and is directed by Yandy Laurens.

Yandy said that the film takes audiences through the life journey of Jonathan Riady who has resettled in Croatia and established himself as a successful photographer.

Soon a mysterious woman appears at his doorstep, and she claims to be his wife from the future.

Sheila said, her character, Sore, warns Jonathan that he has to take good care of his health by quitting smoking and drinking alcohol.

Dion who plays Jonathan said, each time they meet in a time loop, his character will absorb some of the things that he learnt from Sore in her earlier visit.

snippet.title: Ultras Malaya march to US Embassy, light flares in pro-Palestine rally
snippet.description:
Hundreds of protesters, believed to be from Ultras Malaya, marched to the US Embassy in Kuala Lumpur in solidarity with the Global Sumud Flotilla.

The group began near The Linc KL, carrying a banner that read “Merdeka Palestin,” lighting flares and chanting anti-Israel slogans as they moved along Jalan Tun Razak around 9pm.

They stopped directly in front of the embassy compound, waving Palestinian flags and igniting more flares as chants continued.

Earlier in the day, thousands had gathered at the same location, demanding stronger international action over Israel’s blockade of Gaza.

The rally began at 3.45pm, with participants marching from The Linc KL, holding banners that read “Down with Israel” and “Reject Zionists,” while chanting “Free Palestine.”

snippet.title: MACC probes tyre industry over price manipulation, import duty leakages
snippet.description:
The Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (MACC) is investigating the tyre industry over possible price manipulation, which is putting a strain on consumers.

One major issue is the importation of up to 300 containers of tyres each year, some of which may not be safe for Malaysian roads.

It’s also believed that the government could be losing as much as RM70 million a year in import duties on around 100,000 tyres, mostly for heavy vehicles. 

This comes amid rising tyre prices, which have jumped 5 to 10 per cent in recent years, with some prices even tripling since 2022. 

There are increasing concerns about the quality and safety of imported tyres sold locally.

snippet.title: Sabah Electricity worker loses grip, swept away by raging Keningau floodwaters
snippet.description:

The man, in his 30s, had earlier carried out maintenance work with two colleagues near a suspension bridge.

They attempted to cross a concrete bridge but were hit by strong currents. Two managed to reach the riverbank, while the victim lost his grip on a rope and was carried away.

Keningau Fire and Rescue chief Senior Fire Superintendent Severinus@Mohd Nidzam Sainkui said an emergency call was received at 9.57pm, and a team of nine firefighters with an engine and EMRS vehicle was deployed.

snippet.title: Lawyer lodges police report over leaked information in Zara Qairina inquest
snippet.description:
Lawyer Datuk Ram Singh has lodged a police report over the leaking of information involving a child witness in the inquest into the death of Zara Qairina Mahathir.

Ram, who represents the child witness referred to as Student A, said the report was lodged at the Luyang police station at about 4pm yesterday.

The lawyer had said that the leaked information included the witness's statement, which was meant to be tendered in the Coroner's Court, but had instead been widely circulated on social media, including WhatsApp.

He added that a video uploaded to TikTok also revealed the names of the five students.

The inquest into the death of Zara Qairina Mahathir was adjourned on Friday after the witness was deemed emotionally unfit to testify.

snippet.title: Ejen Ali director found dead by river, just a week after getting married
snippet.description:
The body of a man found by the riverside in Kampung Batu Putih yesterday (Sept 24) has been confirmed as Andi Abdul Ghani Kadir, 41, director of the popular animated film Ejen Ali.

His remains were discovered at 11.25am along the riverbank, near the location where he was reported missing the day before.

The incident occurred on Tuesday evening while Andi and his 33-year-old wife were travelling from Tawau to Kota Kinabalu.

The vehicle, driven by his wife, is believed to have lost control and veered off the road. Andi is said to have exited the car shortly after and was last seen near the Kampung Batu Putih river bridge.

Kinabatangan Fire and Rescue Station chief Hairi Otuh said a distress call was received at 5.03pm on the day of the incident, prompting the deployment of four personnel to the scene.

snippet.title: Poor student from PPR now a doctor, fulfils promise to father
snippet.description:
Six years ago, he was a poor student living in public housing, uncertain whether he could pursue his dream of becoming a doctor.

Today, Dr Abdul Manaf Abdul Aziz, 24, stands proudly among 131 graduates of the International Islamic University Malaysia (IIUM) Kuantan campus, having fulfilled a promise he made to his father in 2019.

Overcome with emotion, he said he was grateful to have fulfilled a promise he made to his father, Abdul Aziz Osman, back in 2019, without burdening his family financially, thanks to the support of many caring individuals and organisations.

The third of five siblings, Abdul Manaf expressed deep appreciation to all who helped him pursue a medical degree, especially given the added challenges of growing up without a mother.

He was speaking at the IIUM Kuantan Medical Oath-Taking Ceremony, which was held recently to celebrate 131 new graduates from the university's Kulliyyah of Medicine.

snippet.title: Trump announces Gaza peace plan, with Netanyahu backing
snippet.description:
President Donald Trump unveiled a wide-ranging Gaza peace plan on Monday and won cautious backing from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who warned he was still ready to "finish the job" against Hamas.

However, Hamas had yet to comment and Netanyahu's warning reflected the complexities lying ahead.

The 20-point plan, which Trump has also circulated to Arab leaders, calls for a ceasefire, release of hostages by Hamas, disarmament of Hamas and gradual Israeli withdrawal from Gaza. 

Other key points include deployment of a "temporary international stabilisation force" and creation of a transitional authority headed by Trump himself and featuring other foreign leaders.

The deal would demand Hamas to fully disarm and be excluded from future roles in the government. However, those who agreed to "peaceful co-existence" would be given amnesty.

Following Israeli withdrawal, the borders would be opened to aid and investment.

snippet.title: Two popular student hangouts in Gelugor ordered to close over hygiene violations
snippet.description:
Two popular restaurants near a higher education institution in Gelugor were ordered to close for 14 days after health inspectors found cockroaches and filthy conditions.

One restaurant, a student favourite, had cockroaches crawling on the walls and kitchen, rat droppings on an unused fridge, and food handlers without typhoid vaccinations or training.

The Northeast District Health Office issued the closure under Section 11 of the Food Act 1983, recording 11 offences and issuing RM1,000 in compounds.

An adjacent Arabic restaurant was also shut down after cockroaches and droppings were found in its kitchen. It received the same RM1,000 compound for poor hygiene and lack of vaccination records.

snippet.title: Magistrate orders Maniishapriet murder case transferred to Shah Alam High Court
snippet.description:
A magistrate's court in Sepang has ordered the murder case involving a couple accused of killing and abetting the killing of 20-year-old university student Maniishapriet Kaur Akhara in Cyberjaya last June to be transferred to the Shah Alam High Court.

The order was issued by magistrate Khairatul Animah Jelani after she granted the request of Deputy Public Prosecutor Raja Zaizul Faridah Raja Zaharudin to move the case against M. Sri Darvien, 19, and his girlfriend D. Thineswary, 19.

Sri Darvien, an unemployed man, is charged with murdering Maniishapriet at a condominium in Cyberjaya on June 23.

He faces charges under Section 302 of the Penal Code, which carries the death penalty or, if not sentenced to death, a maximum of 40 years in prison and 12 strokes of the rotan.

Thineswary, who shared a residence with the victim, is charged with abetting Sri Darvien in the murder of Maniishapriet, an offence committed through conspiracy.

snippet.title: Petronas Towers, Merdeka 118 safe, built to global standards
snippet.description:
Malaysia’s iconic skyscrapers, including the Petronas Twin Towers and Merdeka 118, are built to international standards to withstand natural forces such as tremors.

Construction Industry Development Board (CIDB) senior general manager for technology and business development, Ir Rofizlan Ahmad, said this was factored in despite Malaysia not being in a major earthquake zone.

The Petronas Twin Towers use a double-deck skybridge to channel forces during tremors and deep foundation piles for stability, while Merdeka 118 applies a modern outrigger structural system that connects the building’s core to its outer columns, helping it withstand strong winds and moderate tremors.

CIDB ensures compliance with construction standards and worker accreditation, while local authorities, engineers and building owners are responsible for monitoring and inspections.

Recent mild tremors in Segamat, Johor, have raised public concern about the resilience of the country’s buildings.

snippet.title: FIFA reveal 7 banned players have no links to Malaysia
snippet.description:
FIFA have released the full reasoning behind the disciplinary action taken against the FA of Malaysia (FAM) and seven Harimau Malaya heritage players, confirming that inconsistencies were found in the original documents submitted during the players' registration process.

In its official report titled "Notification of the Grounds of the Decision" dated Oct 6, 2025, FIFA's Disciplinary Committee said the sanctions were imposed for violations under Article 22 of the FIFA Disciplinary Code, involving the falsification and alteration of official documents.

The investigation revealed that several supporting documents submitted by FAM, including birth certificates of the players' grandparents, contained details that did not match the original records in the players' actual countries of birth.

Checks found that the individuals listed as the grandparents of the seven players were not born in Malaysia, contradicting what was stated in the documents provided to FIFA.

snippet.title: Anwar cleared in probe into alleged foreign bank accounts, says MACC
snippet.description:

snippet.title: Protestors, dockworkers make good on vow to disrupt Israel bound cargo
snippet.description:
Protests and dock strikes have erupted worldwide following Israel’s interception of the Global Sumud Flotilla and the arrest of hundreds of activists on board.

In Italy, dockworkers in Genoa sparked the movement by blocking port access on Sept 22, warning that all Europe-bound shipments to Israel would stop if contact was lost with GSF volunteers. 

The strikes have since spread to Livorno and Naples, drawing hundreds of thousands in solidarity.

Similar actions were reported in Ireland, the United States, and Australia, where protesters blocked major ports to halt Israel-bound cargo.

The GSF, carrying food and medicine to Gaza, was seen as one of the last humanitarian missions to the besieged enclave before being seized by Israeli forces.

snippet.title: 2026 Budget: Higher taxes for cigarettes and alcohol
snippet.description:
The government will raise excise duties on cigarettes and alcoholic beverages starting Nov 1, to curb smoking and promote healthier lifestyles.

Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said the hike includes an increase of two sen per cigarette stick, RM40 per kilogramme for cigars and cigarillos, and RM20 per kilogramme for heated tobacco products.

He said the move is part of wider health reforms to reduce non-communicable diseases such as heart disease and diabetes.

Import and sales tax exemptions for nicotine replacement therapy products will be extended until Dec 31, 2027, and expanded to include nicotine mist and lozenges.

Excise duties on alcoholic beverages will also rise by 10 per cent from Nov 1, to discourage excessive drinking and promote healthier habits.

He announced this while tabling the Budget in the Dewan Rakyat today.

snippet.title: Malaysia Day a testament to courage, diversity and unity -  PM
snippet.description:
Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said today that Malaysia Day is not merely about commemorating the historic union of diverse regions and cultures, but stands as a symbol of a nation's unwavering resolve to remain united in diversity.

He said the annual celebration on Sept 16 serves as a reminder of the courage of past generations who resisted colonial rule, upheld dignity and laid the foundation of an independent and sovereign nation.

Anwar said that Malaysia's strength stems from its people who uphold values of humanity, justice, and solidarity, reinforced by robust national institutions and good governance.

He said Malaysia's cultural richness and societal diversity must continue to be celebrated as a blessing that strengthens the bonds of brotherhood.

The prime minister also stressed that Malaysia must continue to be projected as a just, prosperous, and civil and compassionate nation, to be passed on to future generations as a strong and dignified nation-state.

snippet.title: Sabah State Assembly dissolved to make way for polls
snippet.description:
The Yang di-Pertua Negeri of Sabah, Tun Musa Aman, has consented to dissolve the state assembly, paving the way for the 17th Sabah state election.

Chief Minister Datuk Seri Hajiji Noor made the announcement, confirming that all 73 constituencies will be contested—following a 2019 motion that expanded the assembly from 60 seats.

The new seats include Bengkoka, Mangaris, Pintasan, Pantai Dalit, Darau, Tanjung Dumpil, Dambai, Tulid, Telupid, Sungai Manila, Lamag, Segama and Kukusan.

In the 2020 snap polls, Hajiji led Sabah Perikatan Nasional in a coalition with BN and PBS to unseat the Warisan–PH government. That coalition, later formalised as Gabungan Rakyat Sabah, won 38 seats.

Following the 2022 General Election, Hajiji and Bersatu assemblymen left the party to form Parti Gagasan Rakyat Sabah, aligning with the federal unity government.

The upcoming election is expected to reshape Sabah’s political landscape once again.

snippet.title: MMEA detains influencer for car photoshoot at sea
snippet.description:
A social media influencer has been arrested by the Malaysian Maritime Enforcement Agency (MMEA) after placing a car on a platform at sea for a photoshoot.

The arrest took place during Operation Iman near Pulau Bidong, about 16 nautical miles off Kuala Terengganu.

Authorities say the stunt, carried out on a platform towed by a passenger boat, violated the Merchant Shipping Ordinance 1952 (MSO).

A second escort boat without a valid license was also detained.

In total, 12 Malaysians — including the influencer, crew, and passengers were taken into custody.

Both boats and those detained were brought to the Terengganu State Maritime Jetty for investigation.

The case is being investigated under the Merchant Shipping Ordinance for license violations, operating without a valid license, and illegal towing activities.

snippet.title: 2026 Budget: Retail, mall groups seek gradual SST rollout
snippet.description:
Retail and mall groups are urging the government to ease the impact of the new 8 per cent service tax on commercial property rentals in the 2026 Budget. 

They want it phased in gradually, starting at 4 per cent, and also propose cutting the tax on construction works. 

Without changes, they warn retailers could face up to RM1.5 billion in extra costs each year, which may push up rents and prices for consumers, strain mall operators, and hurt one of Malaysia’s key economic drivers.

Retailers are already facing rising wages, new staff-related costs, and global price pressures that are squeezing margins and slowing growth.

snippet.title: How I lost my mum to a silent heart condition
snippet.description:
It was supposed to be the proudest day of her life. As Dr Aliza Shah Muhammad Shah received her PhD scroll, she ached for the one face missing in the crowd — her mother’s.

She had dreamt of her recently, healthy and smiling. Aliza thought she had a second chance; so she rushed to hold her mother’s hand, urging her to get a heart check-up. 

But it was only a dream. The painful truth was that her mother was gone.

It all began with what seemed like a small wound on her toe. Nothing alarming at first. 

But the wound worsened, and the pain became unbearable. 

Eventually, her mother agreed to be admitted to the hospital and accepted the need for amputation.

But the tests revealed an even harsher reality. Her toe had darkened because her heart was too weak to pump sufficient blood to the area.

Doctors had no choice but to amputate her leg. She survived, but her spirit dimmed, and her health declined.

On convocation day, Aliza stood proud — yet grieving. The one person she most wanted to see was no longer there.

Her mother’s loss teaches a hard truth: caring for your heart isn’t optional — it’s a chance to protect the ones you love.

----------------------------------

snippet.title: RM1.99 per litre RON95 from Sept 30
snippet.description:
RON95 fuel will be priced at RM1.99 per litre for all Malaysians from Sept 30, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said today.

Police and military personnel will enjoy the new rate from Sept 27, while Sumbangan Tunai Rahmah (STR) recipients can access the cheaper fuel from Sept 28.

Anwar said the fuel subsidy initiative, Budi Madani RON95 (BUDI95), will reduce fuel prices for Malaysians from RM2.05 per litre to RM1.99 per litre.

Speaking at an assembly with Prime Minister's Department staff, he said non-citizens and large companies are not eligible and must pay the full unsubsidised price, which is estimated at RM2.60 per litre.

The unsubsidised figure is still lower than in other countries, including Saudi Arabia (RM2.61 per litre), Indonesia (RM3.22 per litre), the Philippines (RM4.22 per litre), Thailand (RM5.68 per litre), and Singapore (RM9.02 per litre).

Anwar said all citizens with a valid driving licence, some 16 million people, are eligible for the RON95 subsidy.

snippet.title: Army takes charge as deadly youth uprising ousts Nepal’s leader
snippet.description:
Nepal’s capital is under military control after a youth-led uprising forced Prime Minister KP Sharma Oli to resign.

The unrest erupted Monday over a sweeping social media ban and deep-rooted corruption. By Tuesday, protesters had torched parliament, government offices, and the former PM’s residence.

At least 19 people were killed in the crackdown. Tanks now patrol Kathmandu’s scorched streets, with the army warning that vandalism and looting will be treated as criminal offences.

General Ashok Raj Sigdel has urged protesters to stand down and seek dialogue.

International voices, including the UN and India’s Prime Minister Modi, are calling for restraint.

snippet.title: Three diaries, books and loose pages belonging to Zara handed over to police, says witness
snippet.description:
The Coroner's Court heard today that several diaries and an exercise book belonging to the late Zara Qairina Mahathir were found by her teachers before being handed over to police for investigation.

Hostel chief warden Azhari Abd Sagap, 31, testified that on July 16, at about 11.15am he was informed that two diaries, one green and the purple, had been discovered inside Zara's locker by a teacher, Gloria.

The next day, July 17, the eighth witness said another teacher, Miswati, found a brown diary and an exercise book while helping to clear Zara's locker in the hostel.

Azhari said he had instructed Cikgu Miswati to arrange Zara's belongings and place them in the isolation room on the lower second floor of the hostel building, after Zara's mother informed him of her intention to collect her daughter's items that same day.

The books were subsequently passed to Cikgu Yuslina.

snippet.title: Mother, son among eight arrested in MACC's Op Rentas
snippet.description:
A mother and her son were among eight enforcement officers arrested in MACC’s latest Op Rentas crackdown.

The duo, detained in Negri Sembilan, are linked to a counter-setting syndicate accused of accepting bribes to bypass immigration procedures.

MACC seized RM80,000 in cash and RM50,000 in jewellery from the pair—plus cars, motorcycles, and devices worth over RM140,000.

Six other suspects—five men and one woman—were found with RM12,000 in cash, US$5,000, 2,360 baht, and jewellery worth RM200,000.

Telecommunication devices worth RM29,000 were also confiscated.

Authorities froze Tabung Haji and ASB accounts totalling RM1 million.

MACC says all suspects are believed to have facilitated illegal entry of foreign nationals in exchange for bribes.

snippet.title: Nearly 200 rounded up during immigration crackdown in 'Little Pakistan'
snippet.description:
Nearly 200 people were arrested during a major immigration crackdown along Jalan Sultan Azlan Shah, also known as “Little Pakistan,” in Kuala Lumpur.

Undocumented migrants attempted to evade arrest by running, crying, and even pretending to faint.

Kuala Lumpur Immigration Director Wan Mohammed Saupee Wan Yusoff said 45 business premises were inspected, and those detained included 150 Pakistanis, 21 Bangladeshis, 10 Indians, and several others.

Three local women suspected of employing undocumented migrants were also arrested, and authorities vowed to act against repeat offenders.

Officials urged illegal immigrants to join the ongoing repatriation programme to avoid detention, investigation, and possible prosecution.

snippet.title: Genting launches RM6 7bil offer to take Genting Malaysia private
snippet.description:
Genting Bhd has launched a RM6.74 billion conditional offer to acquire all remaining shares in Genting Malaysia Bhd, aiming to take the gaming and resort operator private.

The group is offering RM2.35 per share for 2.87 billion shares, or 50.64 per cent of Genting Malaysia, which operates Genting’s leisure and casino businesses.

Genting, which already owns 49.36 per cent, said the deal will strengthen its control and allow continued consolidation of the company's financial results.

The acquisition will be funded through up to RM6.3 billion in debt and internal funds, offering shareholders a premium of up to 22.9 per cent over the past year’s market prices.

snippet.title: EPF to raise excess savings threshold from 2026
snippet.description:
The EPF is raising the savings threshold from 2026 to give members more flexibility with their retirement funds. 

Starting that year, members can withdraw extra savings once they pass RM1.1 million, with limits rising to RM1.2 million in 2027 and RM1.3 million in 2028. 

This move reflects rising costs and longer life expectancy.

More Malaysians are making voluntary top-ups and hitting savings targets.

The average savings for those nearing retirement has also gone up.

While the basic savings target will increase to RM390,000 by 2028, it’s a sign of growing awareness and planning. 

Monthly withdrawals are also being explored to offer more stable, long-term financial security.

snippet.title: Saifuddin: Kelantan police chief's remark on statutory rape is his view
snippet.description:
Home Minister Datuk Seri Saifuddin Nasution Ismail has described Kelantan police chief Datuk Mohd Yusoff Mamat's remarks on underage sexual cases involving consent as his personal opinion.

He said Yusoff's suggestion that girls involved in consensual sexual relations with men should also face legal action was based solely on figures and statistics recorded in the state.

He told reporters this at a press conference after inspecting counters at the National Registration Department (NRD) headquarters during the first day of free replacement for faulty MyKad chips today.

Earlier, Kelantan police proposed that existing laws be reviewed, particularly in cases of underage sexual relations involving consent, so that action would not only be taken against the perpetrator but also against their partners.

snippet.title: Royal procession shines in Klang
snippet.description:
Excitement swept through Klang this morning as the royal wedding day unfolded in grand tradition.

At 8.17am, the Sultan of Selangor made his arrival at the palace, greeted with full ceremonial honour as the royal household prepared for the historic day.

Barely half an hour later, at 8.52am, the Raja Muda of Selangor arrived at the Sultan Abdul Aziz Royal Gallery, marking another significant moment in the unfolding proceedings.

By 9.10am, anticipation reached its peak as the much-awaited royal perarakan began. The air pulsed with the beat of kompang, while flags waved high and glittering bunga manggar caught the morning sun. 

Well-wishers thronged the streets, others cheering with pride, as the colourful entourage moved towards Istana Alam Shah. All eyes were fixed on the royal procession, awaiting the moment the Raja Muda would meet his bride.

snippet.title: Malaysia Day celebration kicks off this morning in Penang
snippet.description:
The 2025 Malaysia Day celebration officially kicked off this morning as Malaysians from all walks of life began gathering at the PICCA Convention Centre @ Arena Butterworth, reflecting the nation's enduring bond of unity.

By 9am, the spirit of patriotism had already filled the convention centre, with visitors streaming into the foyer, which was lined with stalls from both government and private agencies.

The Malaysian Information Department (Japen), in collaboration with the Malaysian National News Agency (Bernama), drew crowds with a special photo exhibition showcasing historic moments of the Malaysia Day celebrations.

Carrying the theme "Malaysia Madani: Rakyat Disantuni", the event, held for the first time in Penang, also known as the Pearl of the Orient, offered a variety of engaging activities for the public, such as a family colouring competition and an interactive Malaysia Day quiz.

snippet.title: MACC drops plan to meet FIFA, leaves FAM to resolve documentation mess
snippet.description:
The Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (MACC) says it will not engage FIFA over allegations of falsified documents involving seven heritage players.

MACC said it had already met with the Home Ministry and the National Registration Department, which provided documents on the players’ citizenship applications.

The statement said based on preliminary checks, the MACC found that the issue appears to be related to technical procedures and does not fall within its jurisdiction at this time. Furthermore, no offence has been identified under the MACC Act 2009 so far.

The commission urged the public not to speculate and to allow the resolution process to take its course.

snippet.title: Abu Sahid charged again, over RM145.5mil CBT case
snippet.description:
Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd director Tan Sri Abu Sahid Mohamed was charged in the Sessions Court today with criminal breach of trust (CBT) involving RM145.5 million linked to the construction of the Putrajaya–KLIA Highway (MEX II).

Abu Sahid, who appeared in court in a dark grey suit and was seated in a wheelchair, pleaded not guilty after the single CBT charge was read to him by the court interpreter before Judge Datuk Mohd Nasir Nordin.

As a director of Maju Holdings, Abu Sahid was entrusted with control over company funds in a CIMB Bank account.

He is accused of dishonestly misappropriating RM145,550,000, which had been deposited into an escrow account under Golden Base Construction Sdn Bhd at Maybank Islamic Berhad.

He was charged under Section 409 of the Penal Code, which carries a maximum jail term of 20 years, whipping, and a fine upon conviction.

snippet.title: Malaysian influencer Farah Lee shares first hand account of Gaza flotilla attack
snippet.description:
Malaysian influencer Farah Lee shared her first-hand account of explosions targeting the Global Sumud Flotilla on its way to Gaza.

She said she was awakened at 3am by news that four or five boats had come under attack, with aerial blasts and falling debris damaging some vessels.

Farah posted that participants were told to stay inside the boats as the crew remained on high alert, asking followers to pray for their safety.

Flotilla command centre spokesperson Datuk Dr Sani Araby Al-Kahery said 15 Israeli drones were flying low every 10 minutes, with eight explosions reported nearby.

He added that this was the fourth harassment incident since entering the Mediterranean, calling it an attempt to intimidate a peaceful humanitarian mission.

snippet.title: Former Armed Forces chief Tun Mohamed Hashim Mohd Ali dies
snippet.description:
Former Armed Forces chief Gen (Rtd) Tun Mohamed Hashim Mohd Ali has died of a stroke at the age of 90.

Hashim, one of Malaysia's most accomplished generals, was the brother of Tun Dr Siti Hasmah Mohd Ali, wife of former prime minister Tun Dr Mahathir Mohamad.

Hashim will be buried at the Raudatul Sakinah Muslim Cemetery in Sungai Besi with full military honours.

snippet.title: SNCC confirms all 23 Malaysian volunteers detained by Israeli forces
snippet.description:
The Sumud Nusantara Command Centre has confirmed that all 23 Malaysian volunteers with the Global Sumud Flotilla were officially detained by Israeli forces as of 4.25pm today.

Director-general Datuk Dr Sani Araby Abdul Alim said visual evidence showed the volunteers being taken into custody, and communications have since been cut off.

The vessel Mikeno, which carried Malaysian actress Ardell Aryana, remained stationary off Gaza’s coast, raising speculation that passengers may have already been transferred.

SNCC believes it’s only a matter of time before all volunteers are moved ashore, following patterns seen in previous interceptions.

Earlier today, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim confirmed the arrests and said he has contacted leaders including the Qatari and Turkish heads of government to seek intervention.

snippet.title: MACC raids businesses over sale of unsuitable, uncertified tyres, alleged price manipulation
snippet.description:
The Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (MACC) has launched a probe into the tyre industry, following allegations of price manipulation practices and the sale of tyres believed to be unsuitable for local weather conditions.

A multi-agency raid was conducted across the Klang Valley, including a tyre shop and two warehouses in Shah Alam. 

At one shop in Jalan Kebun, officers found 12 shipping containers stacked four storeys high, with more containers and a makeshift warehouse holding hundreds of tyres, some sold for as low as RM85.

A source close to the investigation said the tyres in question had not been certified or approved for Malaysian road and climate conditions, posing serious safety risks.

The source added that unsuitable tyres wear out faster and unevenly, leading to frequent replacements and higher maintenance costs.


Read more at:

snippet.title: Bloodstains on handwritten papers matched Zara's DNA profile, court told
snippet.description:
Bloodstains found on sheets of paper with the handwriting of the late Zara Qairina Mahathir matched the 13-year-old girl's DNA profile, the Coroner's Court heard today.

Chemist Nor Aidora Saedon, 52, from the Department of Chemistry Malaysia in Petaling Jaya, said the bloodstains were found on a paper marked "Y8", and on a paper marked "Y1",  which were analysed for DNA comparison.

She told the court that the bloodstains were consistent with each other and matched the DNA profile obtained from a bone specimen marked "WK37" and labelled "Zara Qairina Binti Mahathir."

In the previous proceedings on Sept 8, document examiner Nurul Atiqah Mohd Noh had testified that the handwriting on several documents marked "Y1" to "Y15" and "W1" and "W2", which she analysed, was consistent with Zara Qairina's handwriting specimens.

It was also reported that bloodstains were believed to be present on sheets with Zara Qairina's handwriting.

Read more at:

snippet.title: Ex-Tronoh assemblyman devastated as final rape appeal fails, ordered to serve eight years
snippet.description:
Former Tronoh assemblyman Paul Yong Choo Kiong was left shocked and in tears after the Federal Court dismissed his final appeal against his 2019 rape conviction.

The 55-year-old was ordered to serve an eight-year jail term and receive two strokes of the rotan at Kajang Prison, effective immediately.

His distraught wife, children and lawyers rushed to his side as police escorted him from the dock.

Lead counsel Datuk Hisyam Teh Poh Teik said the ruling was devastating for Yong and his family, who had attended both appeal hearings at the Palace of Justice.

snippet.title: Crocodile attack kills boy fishing in Sarawak river
snippet.description:
A 12-year-old boy died after a crocodile attack while fishing in Sungai Kampung Empila, Samarahan, this morning.

Arif Fahmi Aiman Mohd Tinggal was dragged into the river while alone in his boat at 7.30am. His body, with bite marks, was found about 10m from where he was last seen.

Firefighters received the call at 7.53am and sent a team to the scene.

Meanwhile, a search continues for a 32-year-old man believed attacked by a crocodile while prawning in Kampung Lubok Punggor on Monday.

snippet.title: Midnight Fusic gears up for solo concert
snippet.description:
Mark your calendars for a night of musical magic as Midnight Fusic takes the stage for their long-awaited, first solo concert, Midnight Fusic Forevermore 2025.

Set to be held at Zepp Kuala Lumpur at 8pm on Sept 14, it is presented by Oyollo Asia and runs for two hours.

The band comprising Ariff Kamaruddin (vocals and guitar), Adrian Danial (guitar), Firdaus Azmi (bass) and Muaz Rabbani (drums) delivers a compelling fusion of alternative rock and rich pop melodies complete with catchy hooks, emotive vocals, and dynamic instrumentation that resonates with rock and pop fans alike.

Ariff said: "While we were formed in 2013, we only had our first concert was in 2022."

He added that the four of them who are aged 25 cite their main influences as 1980s pop and rock stars especially Michael Jackson, Earth, Wind And Fire and The Smiths.

"Domestically, we are big fans of Hujan and its charismatic leader Noh Salleh."

snippet.title: Illegal taxi driver who charged tourist RM836 to be charged today
snippet.description:
A woman who allegedly attempted to fleece a foreign tourist of RM836 for an illegal taxi ride from Kuala Lumpur International Airport to the city centre will be charged at the magistrate's court today.

The suspect, believed to be in her 40s, will face a charge under Section 205(1) of the Land Public Transport Act for touting and providing services without lawful authority.

Dressed in a light green top and blue jeans, the woman arrived at the court complex with a male companion.

She is scheduled to appear before magistrate Khairatul Animah Jelani.

If found guilty, she faces a fine of up to RM50,000, a jail term of up to five years, or both.

snippet.title: Over 700 schools audited for safety nationwide, says Education Minister
snippet.description:
More than 700 out of 10,000 schools nationwide have undergone safety audits to ensure optimal security standards across educational institutions.

Education Minister Fadhlina Sidek said the audit process is ongoing and has shown encouraging progress, although there is still a long way to go before all schools are fully assessed.

Earlier this week in Lenggeng, Negri Sembilan, Year Three pupil Abdul Fattah Khairol Rizal, died after falling into a sewage drain on school grounds.

In response, Fadhlina said stern action would be taken against any breach of standard operating procedures (SOP) that led to the incident.

snippet.title: Trump's visit a platform for Malaysia to voice firm stance on Palestine - Reezal Merican
snippet.description:

snippet.title: Immigration busts online sex syndicate, 33 arrested
snippet.description:
A prostitution ring which offered services online via websites, WhatsApp, and Telegram has been crippled after the Immigration Department raided three premises in Klang and Puchong.

The raids saw the arrests of 29 foreigners and four Malaysians.

On Wednesday afternoon, the department raided a hotel in Klang, detaining 13 foreign women from Indonesia, Thailand and Vietnam.

The women, aged 19 to 53, are suspected of being involved in prostitution, charging between RM190 to RM960 depending on their nationality.

Two Malaysians, believed to be their minders, were also arrested.

That evening, the department raided two reflexology centres in Puchong, arresting 16 foreign women from Thailand, Myanmar, Laos, and China, aged 20 to 37.

snippet.description:
Tourism, Arts and Culture Minister Datuk Seri Tiong King Sing said he regretted the confusion surrounding a gala dinner linked to Tourism Malaysia, where alcohol was served.

The minister was responding to a question in the Dewan Rakyat today on the ministry's guidelines for a government circular that prohibits serving alcoholic drinks at official government functions.

Tiong said the confusion stemmed from his oversight because he had not made any prior announcement about the gala dinner, which was held in conjunction with the Global Travel Meet exhibition. 

Some 600 tourism industry players from abroad took part in the exhibition, which recorded transactions worth nearly RM420 million.

snippet.title: Couple arrested after car plunges into river, killing two children
snippet.description:
Police have opened an investigation under Section 302 of the Penal Code into the deaths of two children who drowned after their family's parked car slid into Sungai Linggi in Tanjung Agas, Port Dickson, yesterday.

Negri Sembilan police chief Datuk Alzafny Ahmad said a man, believed to be the children's father, and a local woman, aged 46 and 41, respectively, were arrested at the Port Dickson district police headquarters at 8pm last night following discrepancies in their statements about the incident.

Checks revealed that the man had a record of 16 prior offences, including four outstanding cases related to fraud and other crimes, while the woman had no criminal record.

He said that both suspects would be brought to the Seremban Court today for a remand application.

snippet.title: All 23 Malaysian GSF volunteers detained, says PM
snippet.description:
All 23 Malaysian volunteers with the Global Sumud Flotilla have been arrested, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim has confirmed.

Anwar said he has contacted Qatari Prime Minister Sheikh Mohammed Abdulrahman Al Thani and Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, and plans to speak with Egyptian President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi.

Together with Foreign Minister Datuk Seri Mohamad Hasan, Anwar has also reached out to other leaders, including US Secretary of State Marco Rubio, urging intervention for the volunteers’ release.

He condemned the arrests, saying the volunteers were targeted for their humanitarian efforts to help the sick, women, and children in Gaza.

Anwar called for an end to Israel’s actions and prayed for the safe release of the volunteers and uninterrupted humanitarian aid to Palestine.

snippet.title: Three friends charged with robbing, brandishing parangs at elderly sisters
snippet.description:
Three friends, all of whom have prior criminal records, including for robbery, were charged in the Sessions Court in Batu Pahat today with robbing and brandishing parangs at two elderly sisters last month.

The accused, Wong Chong Loong, Sim Jia Ie and Ngoh Tian Song, all painters by trade, pleaded not guilty to two charges read out by the court interpreter before Judge Osman Affendi Mohd Shalleh.

According to the first charge, they were jointly accused of committing gang robbery using two parangs measuring 57cm and 53cm against a 70-year-old female victim, fleeing with a mobile phone and cash.

In the second charge, they allegedly robbed a 68-year-old woman using the same weapons, stealing her multi-purpose vehicle and cash.

They were charged under Section 395 of the Penal Code, read together with Section 397, which carries a penalty of up to 20 years in prison and whipping upon conviction.

snippet.title: Cops uncover syndicate supplying drug-laced herbal drinks in KL raid
snippet.description:
Police foiled a syndicate distributing MDMA-laced herbal drinks following a raid on a condominium in the city last week.

Dang Wangi police chief Assistant Commissioner Sulizmie Affendy Sulaiman said a team from the district headquarters' Narcotics Criminal Investigation Department conducted the raid at 10.20pm last Thursday at a condo in Jalan Yap Kwan Seng. They arrested two men aged 30 and 32.

He said the case was being investigated under Section 39B of the Dangerous Drugs Act 1952 for drug trafficking, which carries the death penalty or life imprisonment, along with a minimum of 12 strokes of the cane upon conviction.

Sulizmie said the drugs were intended for distribution to entertainment outlets across the Klang Valley, with each bottle of the drug-laced drink sold at RM450.

snippet.title: Family identifies man's body found in suitcase behind flats
snippet.description:
The body of a man found with his neck slashed and hands tied inside a suitcase near the Ampang Jajar Flats has been identified as Lee Boon Han, 31.

The identification was made this morning at the Forensic Unit of Seberang Jaya Hospital by Lee's father, who had reported him missing on Wednesday after he failed to return home.

According to the family, Lee had told them he was travelling to Perlis for work-related matters but became unreachable soon after.

Checks at the hospital showed the elderly man leaving the forensic unit in a sorrowful state before informing family members and acquaintances that the body was his son.

snippet.title: Sessions Court grants forfeiture of RM169mil allegedly belonging to Ismail Sabri
snippet.description:
The Sessions Court today ordered more than RM169 million in cash, allegedly belonging to former prime minister Datuk Seri Ismail Sabri Yaakob, to be forfeited to the government.

Judge Suzana Hussin made the ruling after allowing the prosecution's application to seize the funds, as no third party had come forward to contest the forfeiture.

She said the court had no grounds to withhold the order, as neither Ismail Sabri nor his former political secretary, Datuk Mohammad Anuar Mohd Yunus, both named as respondents, had objected to the application.

She said therefore, the money is forfeited to the government under Section 41(1) of the Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (MACC) Act.

snippet.title: URA Convention: Speakers demand bill redrafted before Parliament tabling
snippet.description:
The Urban Renewal Act (URA) Convention today adopted three resolutions, with speakers urging the bill to be redrafted to address public concerns.

The first resolution calls for the bill to be withheld from Parliament until 14 weaknesses are addressed. These include stricter oversight of developers, fair compensation, higher consent thresholds, and government intervention in abandoned or unsafe projects.

The second resolution seeks a comprehensive review of 10 planning and real estate laws, among them the Land Acquisition Act, Housing Development Act, and Local Government Act.

Umno vice-president Datuk Johari Abdul Ghani cited the abandoned Plaza Rakyat project as proof that current laws fail to adequately address commercial interests in redevelopment.

Meanwhile, the third resolution proposes creating a dedicated Urban Redevelopment Authority to regulate projects and resolve disputes.

Johari said the convention featured 11 speakers from diverse backgrounds and received over 1,200 responses nationwide.

snippet.title: Badminton world champion Tang Jie has Taiwanese roots
snippet.description:
Few realise Malaysia’s new mixed doubles world champion Chen Tang Jie is half-Taiwanese.

Tang Jie, who clinched Malaysia’s first-ever world title in the event with Toh Ee Wei in Paris, has paternal roots in Taiwan.

At the Taiwan Open two years ago, his sister Chen Yi Wen surprised him by sneaking in as a “reporter,” leaving the siblings laughing in the mixed zone.

In another clip, Tang Jie, who was born in Ipoh, Perak, but grew up in Negri Sembilan, confirmed his paternal roots in Taiwan and said he was thrilled to celebrate with relatives who were present.

On Sunday, Tang Jie–Ee Wei beat China’s Jiang Zhen Bang–Wei Ya Xin 21-15, 21-14 — Malaysia’s first mixed doubles medal since 2006, and first world title since 2022.

snippet.title: RON95 subsidy keeps lid on inflation, steadies spending
snippet.description:
The government’s targeted RON95 subsidy is keeping inflation in check and helping Malaysians maintain their spending power. 

Economists say cheaper fuel keeps transport costs low and protects spending power on daily needs.

From Sept 30, Malaysians with a valid licence can buy RON95 at RM1.99 per litre, capped at 300 litres a month.

Foreigners will pay RM2.60, while about 16 million locals are set to benefit.

Analysts believe the move will have little to no impact on inflation, with some even seeing a slight drop effect. 

They add that targeting foreigners first, while keeping subsidies for Malaysians, balances relief for households with government savings.

snippet.title: Woman charged after rushing towards Sultan Nazrin at Merdeka parade
snippet.description:
A 41-year-old woman who rushed towards the Sultan of Perak, Sultan Nazrin Muizzuddin Shah, during the state-level National Day parade on Aug 31 was charged in the Ipoh Magistrates' Court today.

The accused was charged under Section 352 of the Penal Code, which provides for a prison term of up to three months, a fine of up to RM1,000 or both upon conviction.

According to the charge sheet, Nurhaswani Afni Mohamad Zorki was accused of committing criminal force against the Sultan.

The offence was allegedly committed in front of the Ipoh Town Hall on Jalan Panglima Bukit Gantang Wahab at about 8.20am during the parade.

Nurhaswani, who appeared calm, nodded in understanding as the charge was read before Magistrate Mohd Harith Mohd Mazlan.

Deputy Public Prosecutor Nasrul Hadi Abdul submitted that no plea be recorded, as an initial report from Hospital Bahagia Ulu Kinta (HBUK) indicated that the accused suffers from schizophrenia.

The case has been fixed for mention on Oct 8.

snippet.title: Abu Sahid's wife claims trial to RM67 million money laundering charge
snippet.description:
The wife of Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd director Tan Sri Abu Sahid Mohamed today claimed trial at the Sessions Court to a charge of money laundering involving almost RM67.14 million allegedly linked to the proposed Putrajaya-KLIA (MEX II) highway project.

Puan Sri Noor Azrina Mohd Azmi,48, who is also a director of Maju Holdings, was accused of receiving the funds into her personal bank account from Abu Sahid's account, believed to be proceeds from illegal activities.

Clad in a black blazer and a blue shirt, Noor Azrina entered her plea before judge Rosli Ahmad.

Lawyer Datuk Hisyam Teh Poh Teik stood next to Noor Azrina, who was in the dock, as the charge was read out to her.

She was alleged to have committed the offence at a bank in Bukit Tunku between March 6, 2017 and Nov 27, the same year.

The charge, under Section 4(1)(b) of the Money Laundering, Anti-Terrorism Financing and Proceeds of Unlawful Activities Act (AMLA), is punishable under Section 4(1). It carries a maximum 15-year jail term and a fine of not less than five times the amount of proceeds from illegal activities or RM5 million, whichever is higher.

Deputy public prosecutor Datuk Ahmad Akram Gharib, who appeared with Mohamad Fadly Mohd Zamry, informed the court that both parties had agreed on bail being set at RM500,000 with one surety and for her passport to be impounded.

snippet.title: Some EVs can't be repaired after crashes, say insurers
snippet.description:
Accidents involving electric vehicles (EVs) can be more complex and costly, sometimes leaving the car beyond repair.

General Insurance Association of Malaysia (PIAM) says rising EV adoption brings new risks for insurers, especially with over 90 per cent sales growth this year.

EVs are built and repaired differently, and as they age, they depreciate faster and cost more to fix.

Some repairs need electrical engineers, not regular mechanics, which makes safety and standards even more important.

PIAM is working with authorities to build up the right skills and workshops, but the support system is still developing.

Right now, premiums remain stable due to semi-regulated pricing, but in other countries, EV insurance is already much higher.

snippet.title: Kelantan's oldest woman, Siti Liah Mamat, dies at 124
snippet.description:
Kelantan's oldest woman, Siti Liah Mamat, died last night at the age of 124.

The mother of 14 and grandmother to more than 40 grandchildren died of old age at her home in Kampung Cherang.

Her grandson, Azhar Mustafa, said the family was by her side when she died at about 11pm.

Known for her calm and gentle nature, family members described her as a loving matriarch who raised her large family with patience and faith.

Siti Liah's remains were laid to rest at the Kampung Rambutan Rendang cemetery around noon today.

Earlier, about 70 family members, relatives, and students from a nearby tahfiz centre performed the funeral prayers.

Siti Liah made headlines in 2021 when, at the age of 120, she became one of the oldest Malaysians to receive the Covid-19 vaccination.

snippet.title: Authorities bust brothel operating in Pulau Indah migrant settlement
snippet.description:
A settlement of undocumented migrants in the Pulau Indah Industrial Park has been found to house a fully operational brothel.

The illegal activity was uncovered during an inspection of a premises located on the third floor of a building in the area.

During the 9.30pm raid, the suspected sex workers managed to escape, believed to have been tipped off by a lookout or "tonto."

A journalist accompanying the enforcement team observed that the premises consisted of 13 rooms, each fitted with air-conditioning.

The brothel was also equipped with a closed-circuit television system monitoring movements from the ground floor to the third floor — believed to be used to detect the presence of authorities.

The brothel is believed to have been in operation for more than six months, targeting primarily local clients, including lorry attendants, and foreign workers in nearby areas.

snippet.title: Mother and daughter survive landslide as house collapses in KK
snippet.description:
A woman and her teenage daughter survived a landslide that completely destroyed their home in Kampung Kopungit, Kepayan, last night.

The incident occurred around 8.45pm when the house of Molly Antutu, 42, and her daughter, Syamimi, 14, collapsed after a loud thud and slid down a slope. Both managed to crawl out to safety with help from neighbours.

Molly sustained minor leg injuries, while her daughter was unhurt.

Kota Kinabalu Civil Defence Force officer Captain Aizex Junior said the landslide measured about 15 metres wide and 25 metres high. Two other landslides were also detected nearby, and monitoring is ongoing.

snippet.title: BUDI95 system can handle 30,000 transactions a minute, says Anwar
snippet.description:
The government's targeted petrol subsidy scheme for RON95, the Budi Madani (BUDI95) initiative, can process more than 30,000 transactions a minute - over 10 times the capacity of the earlier Sumbangan Asas Rahmah (Sara) platform, Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said.

The finance minister said the government had learned from the challenges faced during Sara's implementation and had ensured that BUDI95 would be able to handle sudden spikes in demand.

He said Sara was designed for a smaller scale and could process only about 3,000 transactions a minute, which led to technical hiccups during its initial rollout.

snippet.description:

According to RTD senior enforcement director Datuk Muhammad Kifli Ma Hassan, the summonses involve offences recorded under the Automated Awareness Safety System (AWAS) Summons 53A and Notices 114 and 115.

He urged those with outstanding summonses to take advantage of the special compound offer — a flat rate of RM150 — available for all three types of offences.

The offer began in January and will run until the end of this year.

snippet.title: Pathologist rules out foul play in Zara Qairina's fall
snippet.description:
Queen Elizabeth Hospital (HQE) pathologist Dr Jessie Hiu ruled out the possibility that the late Zara Qairina Mahathir had been pushed or attacked, causing her to fall from the third floor of her dormitory before she was found unconscious beneath the building in the early hours of July 16.

Continuing her testimony on the second day of the inquest into Zara's death at the Coroner's Court today, Dr Hiu dismissed both assumptions based on findings from the site inspection where the teenager was discovered unconscious.

Responding to questions from deputy prosecution chief II Datuk Badiuszaman Ahmad, who is conducting the inquest, Dr Hiu said it was highly likely that Zara had either jumped or swung herself while holding onto the iron grille suspended above the dormitory corridor wall.

During today's proceedings, Dr Hiu also explained several photographs taken during the site inspection, along with a demonstration carried out with HQE medical officers to reconstruct how Zara might have fallen.

The demonstration aimed to determine whether the fall could have happened accidentally or as a result of being pushed from behind.

snippet.title: Former Guantanamo detainee Nazir Lep begins new chapter with marriage in Muar
snippet.description:
After nearly two decades in Guantanamo Bay, former detainee Mohammed Nazir Lep has begun a new chapter—marrying in a modest ceremony in his hometown.

Nazir, 49, tied the knot with Zuraizah Zainal in Kampung Jeram Masjid, Bakri, surrounded by close family and friends.

Known affectionately as “Pak J,” Nazir was arrested in Thailand in 2003 over alleged militant links and repatriated to Malaysia last December.

Guests included Deputy Inspector-General of Police  Tan Sri Ayob Khan Mydin Pitchay. 

Nazir's family says he’s quieter now, but still warm and reflective—often sharing advice on life and faith.

The wedding, steeped in Malay tradition, marks a moment of closure and resilience after years in detention.

snippet.title: Pas warns PN's path to Putrajaya still 'uncertain'
snippet.description:
Pas deputy president Tuan Ibrahim Tuan Man said talk of Perikatan Nasional's (PN) prime ministerial candidate is premature, stressing that the coalition must focus on strategy and cohesion.

He added that despite holding 73 parliamentary seats and four states, PN's path to federal power remains "uncertain."

His remarks come a week after its political partner Bersatu unanimously nominated president Muhyiddin Yassin as prime ministerial candidate for GE16.

Tuan Ibrahim's remarks underscore simmering cracks between Pas and Bersatu, opposition allies to Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim's leadership, with fresh disputes over election funding spilling into public view.

Pas, an Islamic-based party, cast itself as disciplined and forward-looking, urging its partners to stay focused on the bigger prize rather than be distracted by political noise.

snippet.title: Court rejects Rosmah's bid to recuse judge in RM1 25bil solar case
snippet.description:
The Court of Appeal has dismissed Datin Seri Rosmah Mansor’s bid to recuse former High Court judge Datuk Mohamed Zaini Mazlan from her solar hybrid project corruption trial.

A three-judge panel led by Datuk Ahmad Zaidi Ibrahim unanimously ruled the application had no merit.

Rosmah, 74, had also sought a retrial before another judge, citing a leaked draft judgment allegedly prepared by a third party for Zaini in 2022.

The panel, which also included Datuk Azman Abdullah and Datuk Noorin Badaruddin, found she failed to prove any real danger of bias.

snippet.title: 5 family members found dead in landslide, 2 still missing
snippet.description:
Five of the seven family members who were victims of a landslide near Kampung Cenderakasih in Kolombong have been confirmed dead as of 3pm today.

The first victim, identified as Husaima Sarabani, 50, was found at 12.30pm.

Four more bodies were discovered during a search and rescue operation later in the afternoon.

The four other victims have been identified as two siblings, Mohd Ilham Abdullah, 2, and Siti Khadijah Abdullah, 4; their cousin, Mohd Izzan Gandi, 7; and their grandfather, Abdul Halid Darak, 50.

Search efforts are still ongoing for the remaining two victims, a mother, Maslinah Abdul Halid, 29, and her son, Mohd Noriman Abdullah, 9.

snippet.title: Bersatu sacks Wan Saiful, suspends Wan Fayhsal
snippet.description:
Bersatu Supreme Leadership Council member Datuk Wan Saiful Wan Jan and four other party members have been sacked from the party.

The Bersatu Disciplinary Board, in a statement today, also announced that Machang member of Parliament Wan Ahmad Fayhsal Wan Ahmad Kamal has been suspended from the party for one term.

The Bersatu Disciplinary Board has received a written complaint from a party member against several respondents over alleged violations of the party’s Constitution and Code of Conduct.

Following the complaint, the Disciplinary Board carried out an investigation and summoned the respondents for a hearing on Oct 8, 2025, before making a decision in line with Clause 22.5 of the party’s Constitution.

snippet.title: Malaysia to raise Gaza flotilla volunteers' abuse with Trump at Asean Summit
snippet.description:
Malaysia will raise concerns with US President Donald Trump at the 47th Asean Summit in Kuala Lumpur over the alleged mistreatment of Global Sumud Flotilla volunteers detained by Israeli forces.

Foreign Minister Datuk Seri Mohamad Hasan said the government supports efforts by Centhra to submit a formal report to the UN Human Rights Council.

He confirmed ongoing coordination with Centhra chief Azril Mohd Amin and the Legal Centre for Arab Minority Rights, which documented abuse and denial of basic needs during detention.

Mohamad stressed that the volunteers were intercepted in international waters and never entered Israeli territory illegally.

He said the detainees were treated as offenders despite being outside Israel’s jurisdiction, and Malaysia will demand accountability.

snippet.title: Liverpool legend Sami Hyypia wows Balai Berita
snippet.description:
Liverpool legend Sami Hyypia brought Anfield spirit to Balai Berita Bangsar, delighting over 150 Media Prima staff in a lively meet-and-greet session.

The former Reds captain signed autographs, posed for photos, and shared stories from his career—drawing laughter and applause from passionate fans.

Hyypia praised the crowd’s energy and said Liverpool’s new season looks promising, though adapting to new players and systems will take time.

He reflected on the intense pressure of playing for top clubs, noting that expectations are sky-high and losses feel like disasters.

On modern football, Hyypia admitted today’s tempo and physical demands might challenge even his own defensive style.

He also shared childhood memories from Finland, where snowy winters meant swapping football boots for ice skates—and where mental toughness, or “sisu,” was key to pushing through.

National infrastructure like rail transport is more than just steel and tracks. As the lifeblood of the nation’s economy, it can also echo Malaysia’s lifestyle, heritage and culture.

snippet.title: RM1.99 RON95 for all Malaysians with driving licence
snippet.description:
Malaysians with a valid driving licence will be eligible for subsidised RON95 petrol, which will be sold at RM1.99 per litre from Sept 30.

Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said the initiative, known as Budi Madani RON95 (BUDI95), will benefit some 16 million people.

Anwar said income levels were not a factor in determining eligibility for the RON95 subsidy, similar to the recent RM100 Sara aid initiative. He said this at an assembly with Prime Minister's Department staff.

To get the subsidy, motorists must verify their MyKad at petrol station counters or pumps.

Alternatively, they can use the Touch 'n Go or Petronas' Setel apps, which removes the need to present their MyKad for every transaction.

Non-citizens and large companies are not eligible and must pay the full, unsubsidised price, estimated at RM2.60 per litre.

snippet.title: Zara was accused of stealing a student's wallet, court hears
snippet.description:
Students at SMKA Tun Mustapha had spoken about an alleged theft case involving the late Zara Qairina Mahathir prior to the 13-year-old's death.

The inquest's fifth witness, security guard Linah Mansoding, told the Coroner's Court that students had talked about Zara being accused of stealing from another student, referred to as "A".

The school guard testified that on July 15, A told her she had lost her wallet.

Lawyer Shahlan Jufri, who is representing Zara's family, examined Linah over the alleged theft before Coroner Amir Shah Amir Hassan.

Linah also testified that student A had reported the missing wallet to senior students.

She said one of the wardens, Ustaz Rizani, had followed up on the allegations by speaking to two students and interviewing others individually.

snippet.title: Heavy rain, strong winds to lash several states, MetMalaysia issues warnings
snippet.description:
The Malaysian Meteorological Department (MetMalaysia) has issued warnings of thunderstorms, heavy rain and strong winds in seven states until 12pm today (Sept 15).

According to MetMalaysia, the affected states are Perlis, Kedah, Penang, Perak (Kerian, Larut, Matang and Selama, Hulu Perak, Kuala Kangsar and Manjung) and Johor (Kluang, Mersing, Pontian, Kulai, Kota Tinggi and Johor Bahru). 

In Sabah, warnings cover Kuala Penyu, Beaufort, Keningau and Tambunan in the interior, as well as Papar, Putatan, Penampang, Kota Kinabalu, Tuaran, Kota Belud and Labuan.

The department also said that first-category strong wind and rough sea warnings are in effect for coastal waters off Perlis, Kedah, Penang, Perak, Johor, Pahang, Terengganu, Sarawak, western Sabah and Labuan until 1pm today.

snippet.title: MMC Ports prepares one of Malaysia's largest IPOs
snippet.description:
MMC Ports, Malaysia’s largest container port operator, has been approved to list on the Main Market of Bursa Malaysia.

This marks a major step for the company as it looks to grow its profile and attract investors. 

MMC Ports runs four of Malaysia’s five busiest ports and ranked fifth globally among private terminal operators last year.

With ports along the busy Strait of Malacca, the company is expanding capacity and investing in automation to support growing trade. 

It’s also exploring strategic partnerships to tap into shifting global supply chains.

The IPO offers up to 4.3 billion shares, making it one of the biggest listings in recent years.

snippet.title: Heavy congestion at Bukit Kayu Hitam border expected until Sept 21
snippet.description:
Travellers heading to Thailand via Bukit Kayu Hitam have been warned to expect congestion at the Immigration, Customs, Quarantine and Security (ICQS) Complex until Sept 21.

Bukit Kayu Hitam Border Control and Protection Agency commander SAC Mohd Nasaruddin M Nasir said traffic has been heavy since yesterday, driven by the school holidays and Malaysia Day long weekend. 

Nearly 22,000 people crossed the border between 6am and midnight, including over 17,000 outbound travellers.

He said additional personnel and the Quick Response Team have been deployed, with close coordination with Thai authorities. Travellers were advised to remain patient, follow instructions, and factor in longer waiting times.

snippet.title: Temporary housing aid for landslide victims in Papar
snippet.description:
Temporary housing assistance will be provided to the families affected by yesterday's landslide tragedy that struck two villages in this district, Kampung Mook and Kampung Marahang Tuntul.

Papar Member of Parliament Datuk Armizan Mohd Ali said he had discussed the matter with Limbahau assemblyman Datuk Juil Nuatim to ensure help is extended to the families of the victims.

He said this assistance is in addition to the RM10,000 death benefit announced yesterday by the Chief Minister.

He was speaking to reporters at the Lok Kawi Height Temporary Relief Centre (PPS) here today.

Also present were Limbahau assemblyman Datuk Juil Nuatim and Kawang assemblyman Datuk Ghulam Haidar Khan Bahadar.

Armizan, who is also the Domestic Trade and Cost of Living (KPDN) Minister, added that risk assessments would be carried out at the landslide sites.
