snippet.title: Fadhlina lodges reports over claims linking her to Zara's principal
snippet.description:
Education Minister Fadhlina Sidek has lodged reports with the police and the Malaysian Communications and Multimedia Commission over defamatory claims linking her to the principal of Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Agama Tun Datu Mustapha.

In a Facebook post yesterday, Fadhlina said several individuals had attempted to associate her with the school's principal.

It was previously reported that the principal, as well as the Senior Assistant of Student Affairs and all the school's wardens, were temporarily placed at the Sabah State Education Department until the police investigation into the case of the late Zara Qairina Mahathir is completed.

In the post, Fadhlina also shared a netizen's comment claiming that she has a familial relationship with the principal.

She said legal action would also be taken on the matter and hoped it would serve as a lesson to all parties not to make any speculation.

snippet.title: Netanyahu under fire as Trump slams Israeli strikes on Qatar
snippet.description:
Israel has confirmed it launched airstrikes on Hamas leaders in Qatar, targeting a meeting of senior figures including Khalil al-Hayya and Khaled Meshaal.

The attack followed a deadly shooting in Jerusalem and killed six people, including Hayya’s son and a Qatari security officer.

Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said the strike was a direct response to shooting, while Israel’s ambassador to the United Nations Danny Danon defended it as “the right decision.”

Qatar, a key US ally and Gaza mediator, condemned the strike as a breach of sovereignty.

US President Donald Trump distanced himself, saying he was “not thrilled” and had not approved the operation.

Hamas claims its leadership survived, calling the attack a failed assassination attempt.

snippet.title: TNB staff killed after motorcycle collides with MPV
snippet.description:
A Tenaga Nasional Berhad staff member died after the high-powered motorcycle he was riding crashed into a multi-purpose vehicle (MPV) at Kilometer 52 Jalan Klang-Teluk Intan yesterday.

In the incident at about 1.35pm, the 45-year-old victim died at the scene.

Kuala Selangor police chief Superintendent Azaharudin Tajudin said the crash involved a Yamaha MT09 motorcycle and a Proton Exora.

He said that as the driver was turning right to stop at a restaurant, the victim, who was coming from the opposite direction, could not avoid the collision and hit the MPV.

The victim was confirmed dead by Health Ministry staff while the driver and passenger of the MPV sustained facial injuries.

Azaharudin said the case is being investigated under Section 41(1) of the Road Transport Act 1987.

snippet.title: Cops cripple RM6 million ganja bud syndicate in Selangor
snippet.description:
Police have crippled a syndicate distributing ganja buds in Selangor following a series of coordinated raids that led to the seizure of 173kg of drugs worth nearly RM6 million.

Federal police Narcotics Crime Investigation Department (NCID) director Datuk Hussein Omar Khan said they detained seven local suspects, five men and two women aged between 25 and 41, in four separate raids between Oct 3 and Oct 5.

He said the operations were carried out based on intelligence gathered by the NCID, targeting several locations across Subang Jaya, Petaling Jaya and Selayang.

Hussein said the second operation, conducted along a roadside in Petaling Jaya, saw the arrest of two men and the discovery of 12 plastic packages containing cannabis weighing about 12.5kg inside a Perodua Alza.

He said the third raid at a hotel in Selayang led to the arrest of a man and a woman, with police seizing 2.1kg of cannabis from their hotel room.

Hussein said the syndicate had been operating since September, with its members playing specific roles within the network.

Read more at:

snippet.title: Alliances explained: Who’s who in the Sabah polls
snippet.description:
The Sabah state assembly has been officially dissolved, setting the stage for the 17th state election.

With 73 seats up for grabs, political coalitions are racing to finalise strategies, seat negotiations, and campaign machinery.

Pakatan Harapan and Barisan Nasional have agreed to work together, while Gabungan Rakyat Sabah (GRS) has also announced a pact with PH. But tensions remain, and GRS and BN may still face off due to unresolved seat disputes.

Warisan, led by Shafie Apdal, will contest all seats solo, rejecting alliances and dismissing talk of a “third force.”

GRS has revoked Parti Solidariti Tanah Airku (STAR) and  Sabah Progressive Party (SAPP) as component parties, though both may still cooperate independently.

Perikatan Nasional faces internal friction over its chief minister candidate, while PAS plans to contest at least 15 seats.

The Social Democratic Prosperity Party will also go solo, targeting 36 seats.

snippet.title: Umno wants Urban Renewal Bill referred to parliamentary select committee
snippet.description:
Umno has announced that it will seek for the Urban Renewal Bill (URA), set for its second reading in Parliament next week, to be referred to a parliamentary special select committee. 

The party’s vice-president, Datuk Seri Johari Abdul Ghani, emphasised that this move is crucial to ensure the bill is improved by incorporating public feedback presented at today’s URA convention.

Johari, who leads the party’s URA special task force, pointed out that the resolutions adopted during the convention would first be presented to Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Ahmad Zahid Hamidi. After that, they will be submitted to Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim for further deliberation.

However, Johari also stressed that the government must present a united front in addressing the concerns raised, to move forward with the necessary changes to the bill.

snippet.title: Malaysia, Timor Leste to deepen ties, boost Asean entry efforts
snippet.description:
Malaysia and Timor-Leste have agreed to deepen cooperation across trade, education, health, tourism, and security as Dili prepares to join Asean as its 11th member.

Prime Minister Kay Rala Xanana Gusmao described the meeting with Malaysian Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim as a milestone in bilateral ties, highlighting productive discussions and shared priorities.

Both leaders committed to expanding scholarships, institutional partnerships, and visa-free travel to strengthen cultural and educational exchange.

Malaysia reaffirmed its support for Timor-Leste’s Asean bid and pledged collaboration in defence, training, and maritime security.

The two nations also expressed unity on global issues, including peace, democracy, and support for Palestine.

Malaysia will host the official ceremony marking Timor-Leste’s full Asean membership.

snippet.title: 9 Malaysian volunteers held by Israel to be flown to Turkiye today
snippet.description:
The nine Malaysians who were detained by Israel for taking part in the Freedom Flotilla Coalition and Thousand Madleens to Gaza (FFC TMTG) humanitarian missions are among 95 volunteers expected to be flown to Turkiye today.

Humanitarian Care Malaysia (MyCARE) chief executive officer Kamarul Zaman Shaharul Anwar said the organisation is still waiting for confirmation from Wisma Putra on the status of the detained volunteers.

As of now, he said, all Malaysian volunteers are reported to be in good health.

Last Wednesday, nine vessels named Abd Elkarim Eid, Alaa Al Najjar, Anas Al Sharif, Conscience, Gaza Sunbird, Leila Khaled, Milad, Soul of My Soul and Umm Saad were intercepted by Israeli forces while sailing about 120 nautical miles from Gaza, within the yellow zone.

All vessels were subsequently escorted to Ashdod Port, after which 145 volunteers were taken to Ketziot Prison for further action by Israeli authorities.

snippet.title: FIFA slaps FAM with heavy fine and player bans
snippet.description:
The FA of Malaysia (FAM) and seven naturalised players have been hit with heavy sanctions after FIFA uncovered forged documents used during a key Asian Cup qualifier.

FIFA’s disciplinary committee found FAM guilty of breaching Article 22 of its code, which covers forgery and falsification.

The investigation revealed doctored papers were submitted to clear players for Malaysia’s match against Vietnam on June 10.

FAM was fined about RM1.9 million, while each player received a fine of about RM10,800 and a 12-month suspension from all football-related activities.

The players’ eligibility to represent Malaysia has now been referred to FIFA’s Football Tribunal.

The decision is subject to appeal, and FAM has ten days to request a full written ruling.

snippet.title: RM1.62 million worth of drugs seized, family of 3 nabbed
snippet.description:
Kelantan police crippled a family-run drug syndicate with the arrest of a woman and her two children and seizure of more than RM1.62 million worth of drugs in an operation on Sept 10.

State police chief Datuk Mohd Yusoff Mamat said the suspects — a man and two women, aged between 19 and 60 — were detained during a raid at a house in Desa Rahmat near Panji.

He said police seized 108,000 yaba pills weighing 12.02kg and 37kg of ketum leaves in the raid.

Yusoff said police also seized a Honda motorcycle valued at RM3,200 under the Dangerous Drugs (Forfeiture of Property) Act 1988, bringing the overall value of seizures and forfeitures to RM1.624 million.

Yusoff said the seized drugs and ketum leaves could supply 120,000 drug users, adding the three suspects have been remanded for 14 days until Sept 24.

snippet.title: Marinette enters Red Zone 2 as last GSF vessel pressing on
snippet.description:
The Marinette, the only vessel from the Global Sumud Flotilla still heading towards Gaza, has entered Red Zone 2 as it continues its journey, despite the interception of 42 other ships by Israeli forces.

Adibah Razali, a member of the Sumud Nusantara Command Centre (SNCC) Central Operations Steering Committee, confirmed that the Marinette—which does not carry any Malaysian delegates—is currently travelling at six knots, faster than the average vessel speed of 4.5 to 5 knots.

She added that calculations are still ongoing to determine the ship's estimated time of arrival.

The flotilla’s movements are being tracked using a system developed by the Malaysian Consultative Council for Islamic Organisations (Mapim) under SNCC.

snippet.title: Explosions heard near Gaza-bound Global Sumud Flotilla convoy
snippet.description:
The Gaza-bound Global Sumud Flotilla (GSF) said explosions were heard and unidentified objects dropped near its vessels as they sailed towards the war-torn area.

GSF said the explosions were heard at 1am local time.

The humanitarian initiative, which aims to break the blockade of Gaza, also said communications were jammed.

In an earlier update, the GSF said more than 15 drones hovered at low altitude above its boat, Alma, for several hours, appearing every 10 minutes or so.

Yesterday, it was reported that the GSF convoy was in the fifth day of its second phase of sailing towards Gaza before entering the yellow zone, some 300km from the Gaza coast.

The GSF, which is carrying food, medicine, and a message of peace, is scheduled to arrive in Gaza waters by the end of the month.

snippet.description:
About 850,000 Malaysians spent more than RM50 million on the first day of the RM100 Sumbangan Asas Rahmah (Sara) one-off aid rollout yesterday (Aug 31).

The Finance Ministry (MoF), in a statement, said the overwhelming response from Sara recipients had caused a sudden surge in transactions.

As a result, the payment terminal system operated through the MyKasih network experienced significant slowdowns at several locations, the statement read.

The ministry added that although the system was running more slowly, transactions were still being received and processed.

The ministry also apologised for any inconvenience caused and assured that it would continue to monitor the initiative closely to ensure smooth implementation.

snippet.description:

The 46-year-old suspect was later found dead about three kilometres away from the shop house where the attack happened.

snippet.title: 23 Malaysian GSF volunteers receive new phones from Fahmi
snippet.description:
Communications Minister Datuk Fahmi Fadzil presented new mobile phones to 23 Malaysian volunteers who participated in the Global Sumud Flotilla (GSF) humanitarian mission to Gaza, as a gesture of appreciation for their contributions.

Fahmi said the contribution was intended to facilitate communication and personal matters upon their return home, while enabling the volunteers to continue sharing their experiences and insights from the mission more effectively.

He said the gesture reflected the government's appreciation for the volunteers who represented Malaysia in the GSF mission and provided regular updates throughout their time on board.

The Emirates flight EK342, carrying 27 Malaysian volunteers, including four from the observer vessel, and five lawyers, landed at Kuala Lumpur International Airport Terminal 1 at 10.07pm on Tuesday.

snippet.title: Kedah homes, royal mausoleum inundated as sudden flood hits Langgar town
snippet.description:
About 500 residents of Kampung Makam in Langgar woke up to a sudden flood on Sunday, with water rising overnight and submerging around 100 homes, a religious school, and the Royal Kedah Mausoleum.

Locals were caught off guard, as there had been no heavy rain since Friday. Floodwaters from Sungai Langgar began breaching the village around 5pm, swelling dramatically by morning.

Fried chicken trader Mohammad Sulhi Shahabuddin estimated RM10,000 in losses, saying the current was too strong to act and the water surged without warning.

Resident Yeoh Chiew Looi described chest-deep flooding inside her home, calling it the worst since 2014. Her family of six scrambled to move furniture to higher ground.

Police and welfare officers rescued elderly villagers and registered about 100 evacuees at a relief centre in Pokok Sena.

Authorities continue to monitor the situation as residents assess damage and brace for further developments.

snippet.title: King: Gaza flotilla a noble humanitarian mission
snippet.description:
His Majesty Sultan Ibrahim, King of Malaysia, has praised the Global Sumud Flotilla (GSF) as a noble humanitarian mission aimed at delivering aid to vulnerable groups, including the elderly, women, and children in Gaza facing hunger.

The King acknowledged the Malaysian volunteers' courage in embracing the risks involved to convey a message of humanity.

Sultan Ibrahim also received a briefing on the latest developments regarding the GSF, including efforts by the Malaysian government to secure the release of detained volunteers.

Earlier today, Sultan Ibrahim granted an audience to Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim at Istana Bukit Tunku.

snippet.title: Selangor influenza spike hits schools as cases surge over 80pct in a week
snippet.description:
Influenza cases in Selangor have surged by more than 80 per cent within a week, with most infections traced to educational institutions.

State Public Health and Environment Committee executive councillor Jamaliah Jamaluddin said 64.7 per cent of reported cases originated from preschools to higher education institutions.

She said that a total of 88 outbreak locations have been detected, averaging three new locations each week between March 8 and Sept 27, adding that the Selangor Health Department continues to monitor the situation and conduct on-site risk assessments through its district health offices.

Influenza can cause symptoms such as fever, cough, sore throat, body aches and fatigue, and may lead to severe complications, particularly in the elderly and those with chronic illnesses.

Jamaliah said the state government, together with health authorities, has implemented a free influenza vaccination programme since February for senior citizens with one or more chronic illnesses.

snippet.description:

snippet.title: Two arrested during GSF rally to be investigated for obstruction, say cops
snippet.description:
Two protesters have been arrested outside the US Embassy in Kuala Lumpur during a pro-Palestine and Global Sumud Flotilla solidarity rally.

Police say the men, aged 23 and 32, resisted officers during a commotion involving around 50 participants.

The situation escalated when some began blocking traffic along Jalan Tun Razak. One officer sustained a mouth injury after being elbowed while managing crowd control.

A 54-second video of the arrest has gone viral on Facebook, showing police detaining one of the participants.

Kuala Lumpur police chief Datuk Fadil Marsus reminded organisers to comply with laws governing public assembly, stressing that while peaceful gatherings are protected under the Constitution, firm action will be taken against those who break the law.

snippet.title: Ex-Mex II director pleads not guilty to forgery charges involving RM314mil
snippet.description:
A former director of Mex II Sdn Bhd, a subsidiary of Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd, pleaded not guilty in the Sessions Court today to 17 counts of document forgery involving false claims amounting to RM314,486,100, allegedly linked to the proposed construction of the Putrajaya-KLIA (MEX II) highway project.

Datuk Yap Wee Leong, 68, who appeared in court wearing a lime green batik shirt, entered his plea before Judge Rosli Ahmad.

The charges involve the alleged submission of falsified progress claims for various works, including site clearance, temporary works, earthworks, geotechnical works, drainage, and pavement, purportedly for the MEX II highway project, which was planned to run from the Putrajaya Interchange to KLIA under Maju Holdings.

The offences were allegedly committed between June 2017 and April 2018 at Maju Holdings Sdn Bhd's office at Maju Tower in Jalan Sultan Ismail.

Yap was accused of dishonestly using the claims as genuine despite knowing they were forged.

The charges under Section 471 of the Penal Code are punishable under Section 465 which provides a maximum of two years imprisonment, a fine or both upon conviction.

Deputy public prosecutor Datuk Ahmad Akram Gharib, who appeared alongside Mohamad Fadhly Mohd Zamry, proposed a bail of RM1 million.

snippet.title: 103 and fearless: Special Constabulary ex policewoman Ang Kim Choo recalls jungle patrols
snippet.description:
Former Emergency-era policewoman Ang Kim Choo marked a significant milestone yesterday as she celebrated her 103rd birthday, expressing deep gratitude for a long and meaningful life.

The grandmother of 12 recalled the proudest chapter of her life when she served in the police force as a Special Constabulary (SC) for six years, between April 1954 and June 1960.

During the Malayan Emergency (1948–1960), the country faced a deadly communist insurgency that claimed thousands of lives, with security forces and civilians alike confronting guerrilla attacks, ambushes, and widespread violence.

The single mother and great-grandmother shared that one of her key responsibilities during her service was monitoring delinquent students, some of whom were involved in gangsterism and frequent schoolyard fights.

snippet.title: Indonesia riots: What you need to know
snippet.description:
Indonesia was rocked by violent protests in Jakarta and other major cities on Friday, triggered by anger over the rising cost of living and lawmakers’ lavish perks.

The unrest, fuelled by months of frustration, escalated after a rideshare driver was killed during police action, sparking the deadliest riots in decades.

Protests began on Aug 25 in Jakarta before spreading nationwide, as students, workers, and labour groups demanded tax reforms, higher wages, and an end to outsourcing.

On Aug 27, students stormed the West Kalimantan parliament, while two days later, thousands clashed with police outside the national parliament in Jakarta.

Demonstrations also spread to Surabaya, Medan, Banda Aceh, and other cities.

By Aug 29, riots left at least five dead, with parliament buildings torched, homes attacked, and businesses looted.

On Aug 31, President Prabowo Subianto pledged to cut lawmakers’ benefits to ease tensions, as the military moved to secure the capital and government sites.

Read more at:

snippet.title: Resort cleaner pleads guilty to gun and ammunition charges
snippet.description:
A resort cleaner pleaded guilty in the Sessions Court today to two charges of possessing a pistol and 36 live rounds without a permit at his home in Kampung Paloh, Pintu Geng, on Sept 6.

The accused, Azhar Anual, 50, entered his plea after the charges were read before Judge Nik Habri Muhamad.

According to the first and second charges, Azhar was found in possession of a Glock 26 Gen4 Austria pistol and 36 live bullets without a licence or permit.

He was charged under Section 8 of the Firearms (Increased Penalties) Act 1971, which carries a maximum sentence of 14 years in prison and up to six strokes of the cane, and under Section 8(a) of the Arms Act 1960, which provides for up to seven years in prison, a fine of up to RM10,000, or both.

Deputy Public Prosecutor Kamarul Hasyime Rosli conducted the prosecution, while the accused was unrepresented.

The court fixed Oct 21 for sentencing, and Azhar was not offered bail.

snippet.title: ‘No regrets, we will fight again’
snippet.description:
Malaysia’s women’s doubles pair Pearly Tan and M. Thinaah made history by securing a silver medal at the BWF World Championships in Paris.

The world No. 2 duo fought hard in a nail-biting final before losing 21-14, 20-22, 21-17 to China’s top-ranked pair.

It was Malaysia’s first-ever medal in the women’s doubles category at the world meet.

On their return to Kuala Lumpur International Airport, Pearly and Thinaah received a heroes’ welcome, along with mixed doubles world champions Chen Tang Jie and Toh Ee Wei.

Pearly said they had no regrets about the final and believed their journey was far from over.

Thinaah expressed hope that their achievement would inspire other female athletes in Malaysia to believe that anything is possible with hard work.

snippet.title: Zara Qairina's mother declined post-mortem despite advice, says witness
snippet.description:
The Coroner's Court heard that the mother of the late Zara Qairina Mahathir declined a post-mortem examination on her daughter's body despite having received an explanation.

Dr Logaraj Ratha, 33, from the Forensic Medicine Department of Queen Elizabeth Hospital (QEH), said that since no issues were raised, the hospital released Zara's remains to her mother, Noraidah Lamat, in line with hospital and departmental policy.

Dr Logaraj, the seventh witness in Zara's inquest, said that Noraidah filled in the first paragraph and the claimant signature section of the letter. Her sister-in-law, Nur Shira Abdullah, also filled in her details in the witness section and signed the document.

Earlier, Dr Logaraj said that at 5pm on July 17, he was informed of a death in the Neurosurgery Ward at QEH which was subject to police investigation. The body, identified as Zara, was later transferred from the Neurosurgery Ward to the Forensic Medicine Department.

snippet.title: 'Someone's been stabbed': Resident recounts horror of double killing in Kedah
snippet.description:
A witness recalled the terrifying moment when his wife screamed that someone had been stabbed, just metres from their home in Taman Nona, Kedah.

The witness said, the incident unfolded around 9pm yesterday as he returned with his wife and five children after shopping.

Just as they stepped inside, his wife urged him to come out again after seeing two people struggling before one of them cried for help.

The witness, who has lived in the neighbourhood for two years, said that neither he nor his wife had seen the victims previously.

Police are investigating the deaths, but no arrests have been made.

Forensic officers and K9 units were deployed at the scene overnight to collect evidence.

snippet.description:
The Conscience, a ship carrying 92 activists under the Freedom Flotilla Coalition (FFC) and Thousand Madleens to Gaza (TMTG), has reportedly arrived at the Port of Ashdod.

The update was shared by Humanitarian Care Malaysia (MyCARE) in a statement today.

The ship, which is carrying 92 people comprising medical doctors, journalists, and humanitarian activists, including eight Malaysians, is believed to have arrived at 12.45am Malaysian time.

MyCARE added that lawyers from the Legal Centre for Arab Minority Rights in Israel (Adalah) were present at the port to assess the condition of those detained on behalf of the FFC.

MyCARE also urged the public to pray for the well-being of all detained activists.

Yesterday, nine vessels, including the Conscience, were intercepted by Israeli forces while en route to Gaza.

snippet.title: Global Sumud Flotilla in the red zone: What we know so far
snippet.description:
The Global Sumud Flotilla (GSF) mission to deliver humanitarian aid to Gaza has been intercepted by Israeli forces.

​The Sumud Nusantara Flotilla Command Centre (SNCC) confirmed the developments on Oct 2, as the flotilla entered a restricted "Red Zone" off the Gaza coast.

​The first vessel, the Seulle, crossed into the zone, some 100 nautical miles off Gaza, at about 9.20pm Malaysian time on Oct 1.

​At 1.20am on Oct 2, as the flotilla neared Red Zone 2, some 66 nautical miles off Gaza, the GSF reported detecting more than 20 unidentified vessels on its radar, just three nautical miles ahead of the flotilla.

​By 1.34am, the SNCC issued a red alert over a possible interception, citing 10 reports from Malaysian participants that Israeli warships were forming up, blocking, and surrounding the flotilla's area.

​At 2.42am, the SNCC confirmed that Israeli forces had stormed the GSF vessels Alma and Sirius. The Alma is carrying three Malaysians, while the Sirius has four on board.

----------------------------------

snippet.title: Zoo Negara land sale sparks backlash as public, NGOs demand answers
snippet.description:
Alarm bells have rung out after it was revealed that Zoo Negara had sold off a plot of unused land it had held since 1963 to maintain the upkeep of the national zoo.

Residents of Taman Melawati, near the zoo area, have voiced concerns over the potential development of the land, claiming that the newly gazetted Ampang Jaya Municipal Council Local Plan shows the land has been reclassified for commercial use.

A group of non-government organisations has raised concerns over this matter and demand that the Selangor government explain why it allowed the sale to proceed.

The New Straits Times spoke to Zoo Negara deputy president Datuk Rosly Lana, who said the hilly plot of land, adjacent to the zoo, had never been used since 1963.

He said at the height of the Covid-19 pandemic, Zoo Negara faced a heart-wrenching problem — how to keep thousands of hungry animals alive with barely RM1 million left in its dwindling savings. 

Feeding tigers, giraffes, elephants and other creatures costs the zoo between RM1.3 million and RM1.5 million a month.

With no visitors and no income, desperation forced Malaysia's national zoo to sell the plot of unused land.

snippet.title: Nearly 100,000 homes remain unsold in the first three months of 2025
snippet.description:
Malaysia may be heading for another property glut — nearly 100,000 residential units remain without buyers in the first quarter of 2025.

According to Napic, homes priced between RM200,001 and RM300,000 make up the largest share of unsold stock, followed by those in the RM300,001–RM400,000 range.

Most of these units are still under construction or not yet built, giving developers time to secure buyers — but if left unchecked, they risk becoming abandoned.

12,498 new residential units were launched nationwide, but only 11 per cent were sold within three months.

Condominiums and apartments dominate the overhang, with over 13,000 units unsold.

The median house price is RM359,000, but the national median household income is just RM6,338 — far below what’s needed to afford a typical home.

Selangor, Perak, and Johor lead in unsold units under construction, with thousands more already approved but not yet built.

Housing Minister Nga Kor Ming declined to comment, saying he would respond after verifying the data with his ministry.

Read here: https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2025/09/1268582/nearly-100000-homes-remain-unsold-first-three-months-2025

snippet.title: Loke: Toddler killed in Kajang toll accident wasn't in child seat
snippet.description:
The one-year-old toddler who died in Saturday's Bukit Kajang Toll Plaza crash was not in a child safety seat, said Transport Minister Anthony Loke.

Loke said preliminary findings from police showed that the baby was thrown out from the vehicle.

He emphasised that the issue is not about blaming parents or victims, but a reminder that while many complain about the Transport Ministry's child seat mandates, incidents like this highlight their crucial importance.

Loke added, child seats have safety features to protect children and babies in an accident, adding that not using them puts them in danger.

snippet.title: Ardell collapses while boarding bus at KLIA
snippet.description:
Ardell Aryana collapsed as she approached the door of the bus carrying Global Sumud Flotilla (GSF) volunteers and their families out of Kuala Lumpur International Airport (KLIA) last night.

At the time, Ardell, who was seen carrying her eldest child, appeared pale and weak before collapsing amid the sea of people present to support the GSF volunteers.

Ardell, whose full name is Nurul Hidayah Mohd Amin, is a humanitarian activist and social media influencer. 

She gained significant attention as a participant in the GSF, a civilian-led mission aimed at delivering humanitarian aid to Gaza and challenging the Israeli blockade.

The incident caused a moment of panic. However, auxiliary police quickly rushed to assist Ardell and helped her onto the bus.

Read more at:

snippet.title: RPGT: Property transfer must be reported to LHDN within 60 days
snippet.description:
In Malaysia, both buyers and sellers must report property transactions to the Inland Revenue Board (LHDN) within 60 days.

This requirement covers sales, transfers and assignments, and must be completed via the MyTax portal. Failure to report within the stipulated period may result in penalties or legal action.

The Real Property Gains Tax (RPGT) is imposed to curb speculation and stabilise property prices. It is a tax on profits from property sales, with rates determined by the length of ownership.

For individuals, no RPGT is charged from the sixth year of ownership onwards.

Read more: https://www.nst.com.my/property/2025/09/1272512/rpgt-property-transfer-must-be-reported-lhdn-within-60-days

snippet.title: Pondok school headmaster charged with assault and obscene images
snippet.description:
A headmaster, or 'mudir', of a pondok school was charged in the Sessions Court today with seven counts of physically assaulting a male student and possession of obscene images

Muhammad Aswadi Yah, 46, pleaded not guilty to all the charges before Judge Zulkpli Abdullah.

On the first to sixth charges, the man is charged with physically sexually assaulting the 16-year-old student at a house in Kampung Kubang Batang, Tumpat, from June 2024 to August this year.

The charges are framed under Section 14(d) of the Sexual Offences Against Children Act 2017, which provides imprisonment for up to 20 years and whipping, if convicted.

On the seventh count, Muhammad Aswadi is charged with possessing obscene images on his mobile phone at about 4pm last Aug 29 at the same location.

The offence, under Section 292 of the Penal Code, provides a maximum prison sentence of three years or a fine or both, if convicted.


Read more at:
